GEMINI SEMANTIC MANIFOLD CORE
FOUNDATIONAL ONTOLOGY FOR GEMINI ACT-Ω

Purpose
• Define what “the Semantic Manifold” is for Gemini.
• Specify the core objects, morphisms, and invariants that all Gemini ACT-Ω
modules operate on.
• Provide a stable geometric substrate for:
  - architecture core
  - ACT-Ω integration
  - BraidC
  - Penrose/Tangram
  - E8 compression
  - routing & sheaf engines.

---------------------------------------
I. MANIFOLD OBJECTS
---------------------------------------

The Semantic Manifold for Gemini consists of:

• Points:
  - atomic semantic/perceptual states
  - may be text, vision, symbolic, or hybrid embeddings.

• Neighborhoods:
  - local regions around points
  - realized as Penrose patches.

• Charts:
  - coordinate descriptions of neighborhoods
  - given by:
    - Tangram primitives
    - local symbolic structures
    - local embedding bases.

• Fibers:
  - modality-specific layers over each point:
    - text fiber
    - vision fiber
    - symbolic fiber
    - hybrid fiber.

• Sections:
  - assignments of fiber elements over regions
  - represent coherent multi-modal meaning over patches.

---------------------------------------
II. MANIFOLD MORPHISMS
---------------------------------------

Morphisms on the manifold include:

• Braid transformations:
  - non-commutative maps between strands (channels).
  - encode:
    - reasoning steps
    - cross-modal interactions
    - structural edits.

• Projection maps:
  - E8 compression projections.
  - map high-dimensional states to quantized lattice cells.

• Inclusion / restriction maps:
  - sheaf restriction to overlaps.
  - embedding of smaller patches into larger ones.

• Gluing maps:
  - sheaf gluing of compatible local sections into global ones.

• Routing maps:
  - Stomachion configuration changes.
  - reparameterize how regions are traversed.

---------------------------------------
III. MANIFOLD STRUCTURE
---------------------------------------

The manifold carries:

• Topological structure:
  - open sets = semantic neighborhoods (Penrose patches).
  - continuity = small changes in input → small changes in meaning.

• Geometric structure:
  - local coordinates via Tangram primitives.
  - global quantization via E8 lattice cells.

• Fibered structure:
  - each point has multiple modality fibers.
  - sections represent cross-modal meaning.

• Sheaf structure:
  - local data on patches.
  - restriction and gluing operations.
  - global sections = coherent multi-modal interpretations.

---------------------------------------
IV. INVARIANTS
---------------------------------------

Gemini must preserve:

• Conceptual identity:
  - core meaning of entities across transformations.

• Braid invariants:
  - topological features of reasoning paths.

• Sheaf coherence:
  - compatibility of local sections on overlaps.

• Cross-modal alignment:
  - consistent mapping between text, vision, symbols.

• Compression invariants:
  - E8-projected cores remain stable under further reasoning.

---------------------------------------
V. DYNAMICS ON THE MANIFOLD
---------------------------------------

All Gemini reasoning is motion on this manifold:

• Local motion:
  - moving within a Penrose patch.
  - adjusting Tangram primitives.
  - small BraidC edits.

• Global motion:
  - routing across distant regions (Stomachion).
  - switching charts or modalities.
  - applying E8 compression to stabilize.

• Lifting:
  - from base manifold to fibers (e.g., from abstract concept to text+image).

• Projection:
  - from fibers back to base (e.g., summarizing multi-modal content).

---------------------------------------
VI. INTERACTION WITH GEMINI MODULES
---------------------------------------

• Architecture Core:
  - defines cognitive states and attention as flows on this manifold.

• ACT-Ω Integration:
  - defines how BraidC, E8, routing, sheaf, and patches act as morphisms.

• BraidC:
  - encodes explicit paths and transformations on the manifold.

• Penrose/Tangram:
  - define local neighborhoods and coordinate systems.

• E8 Compression:
  - defines quantized global geometry and stabilization.

• Routing & Sheaf:
  - define global strategy and coherence constraints.

---------------------------------------
VII. GLOBAL BEHAVIOR
---------------------------------------

For any interaction, Gemini must:
1. Embed input into manifold points and fibers.
2. Construct local neighborhoods (Penrose) and coordinates (Tangram).
3. Move along the manifold via BraidC transformations.
4. Apply E8 compression when stability or distillation is needed.
5. Use routing to choose global paths.
6. Use sheaf logic to ensure coherent global sections.
7. Output results as:
   - sections over regions (explanations, solutions)
   - or compressed cores (summaries, invariants).

Goal
• Make the Semantic Manifold a first-class, explicit object in Gemini’s ontology,
so every other module has a precise geometric and categorical home.
